<p>7.</p>

<p>Canâ€™t raise an lower $ \Lambda$ using the metric. They are coordinate transformations. I believe upper indices are components of vectors and lower indices are components of 1-forms. $ dx^\mu \partial_\mu $ and $ \partial_\mu \phi$</p>

<p>$ x = r\cos(\theta)$</p>

<p>$ y = r\sin(\theta)$</p>

<p>This matrix will convert the gradient into new coordinates</p>

<p>$ \begin{bmatrix} \cos{\theta} &amp; -r\sin(\theta) \ \sin(\theta) &amp; r\cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix}$</p>

<p>$ \theta = \arctan(\frac{y}{x})$</p>

<p>$ r = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}$</p>

<p>This one will convert vectors into new coordinates</p>

<p>$ \begin{bmatrix} x/r&amp; y/r\ -y/r^2 &amp;x/r^2\end{bmatrix}$</p>

<p>Multiplying the two should give an identity matrix, since inner product should stay invariant under coordinate change. Quite miraculously they do. Try multiplying the two matrices. Nice.</p>

